title: For Sale/Trade:  harrington & richardson self-loading .32acp
postcontent:
For sale in westminster for $450 or trade for a beretta model 1934 in .32 or .380 - is my self-loading pistol was manufactured during the period 1910-1914,under agreement with webley & scott of birmingham england, and it is in fact, the webley .25 "hammerless" model of 1909.patents were taken out in the US in 1907 and 1909, principally covering the use of twin recoil springs, and the H&R differs from the webley in many ways.
 the webley is hammerless in name only,since it used an internal hammer, and the H&r lockwork was rather different than the webley, probably as a matter of manufacturing convenience.more obvious is the shaping of the barrel and slide; in the webley pattern the slide is open topped with a bridge carrying the front sight.as a result the barrel is slender so the bridge can pass over it on recoil.
 the H&R model uses an open topped slide without a bridge,and the barrel rear section is built up to continue the contours of the slide;there are no rear sights fitted. the external contours of the H&R are more generally radiussed than those of the webley, and the grips are fitted in a different manner.
it was believed that there was little demand for the .25 model and few were made..H&R also produced a .32 model which, while based on webley practice, was not a counterpart of any webley and scott model. it was 'hammerless' ( i.e internal hammer)model with open topped slide and extended barrel, and a short grip safety at the rear of the butt. it also used a coil spring recoil spring above the bolt, instead of the webley v-spring system. this model appeared shortly befor the first world war, and continued to me made into the early 1920's.
this one is clean as a whistlein and out with original holster minor wear , no rust, no pitting. shine in bore strong rifleing. perfect grips 8+1 capacity.   3 0 3  4 3 0  8 1 9 2

Im willing to travel within maybe 30 or so miles from 43050. I will have pics posted later this afternoon.  Thanks for looking. 

Borrowed this from the web-Marlin 512 Slugmaster
Yes, Browning might be getting the most attention but it was not the first production bolt-action gun available with a rifled barrel. That distinction went to the Marlin Model 512 Slugmaster, which was first produced in 1994. Modeled after the company’s long-standing Model 55 models, the most famous of which is the 36-inch barreled Goose Gun, the 512 features a 21-inch fully rifled (one turn in 28 inches) barrel and two-shot detachable-box magazine with rifle sights.

The 8.5-pound gun is built on a checkered birch stock. The 512 is actually a close cousin to the Model 55S (for slug) that Marlin marketed in the 1960s, which featured a 24-inch smoothbore barrel, rifle sights and sling swivels.

Today the root of the bolt handle certainly provides sufficient locking strength since shotgun chamber pressure levels barely reach one-quarter of that of a high powered rifle, which must be front-locked.

The Marlin bolt is mounted well forward, Mannlicher style, and notches in a slot in the receiver top, necessitating a side scope mount (Weaver 10M). A heavy recoil lug is set between the receiver and barrel into a recess in the stock.


Suggested retail for the 512 is in the $350 neighborhood
